<exercises xml:id="Ex-subspace">
	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Let <m>\ell</m> be a line passing through the origin in <m>\R^2</m>. Determine for which vectors <m>v\in\R^2</m>, the subset <m>v+\ell=\{v+x:x\in\ell\}</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^2</m>. Think geometrically.
		</statement>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Find all subspaces in <m>\R^2</m> that contain the vector <m>(2,2)</m>.
		</statement>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Show that a set with two vectors from <m>\R^3</m> can not span <m>\R^3</m>.
		</statement>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Consider a map <m>\pi_1\colon\R^n\to\R^n</m> given by <m>(x_1,x_2,\ldots,x_n)\mapsto (x_1,0,\ldots,0)</m>. Show that the image of <m>\pi_1</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^n</m>.
		</statement>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Find all subspaces of the vector space <m>\R</m> over <m>\R</m>.
		</statement>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Determine whether <m>(8,-2,-7)\in\R^3</m> is a linear combination of the vectors <m>(1,1,1), (-2,0,1), (-1,3,5)\in\R^3</m>. Here we consider <m>\R^3</m> as vector space over <m>\R</m>.
		</statement>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Consider a vector space <m>M_{2\times 2}(F)</m> of <m>2\times 2</m> matrices over a field <m>F</m>. Show that the span of <me>S=\bigg\{\begin{pmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}0\amp 1\\0\amp 0\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}0\amp 0\\1\amp 0\end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix}0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\end{pmatrix}\bigg\}</me> is <m>M_{2\times 2}(F)</m>.
		</statement>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Let <m>V</m> be a vector space over a field <m>F</m>, and let <m>S=\{v_1,v_2,v_3\}\subset V</m>. Suppose that <m>w=\alpha v_1+\beta v_2</m> for some <m>\alpha,\beta\in F</m>. Is <m>\langle S\rangle=\langle\{w,v_2,v_3\}\rangle</m>?
		</statement>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Show that a union <m>W_1\cup W_2</m> of subspaces of a vector space need not be a subspace of <m>V</m>.
		</statement>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<statement>
			Let <m>V</m> be a nontrivial (i.e., <m>V\neq\{0\}</m>) vector space over an infinite field <m>F</m>. Show that <m>V</m> is not a union of a finite number of proper subspaces.
		</statement>
	</exercise>
	<hint>Suppose that <m>V</m> is a union of a finite number of proper subspaces <m>W_i</m>, <m>V=W_1\cup W_2\cup\cdots\cup W_r</m>. We may assume that <m>W_1\not\subset W_2\cup W_3\cup\cdots\cup W_r</m>. Choose <m>w\in W_1\setminus(W_2\cup W_3\cup\cdots\cup W_r)</m> and <m>v\in V\setminus W_1</m>. Consider the line through <m>v</m> and parallel to <m>w</m>, i.e., the set <m>U=\{\alpha w+v:\alpha\in F\}</m>. Show that <m>U</m> is an infinite set and that each <m>W_i</m> contains atmost one vector from <m>U</m>.</hint>
</exercises>